{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","data":{"fields":{"description":"# Committed store compatibility record with a fail-closed capability gate\n\nIntroduce a committed store-level compatibility record (`format_version` +\n`required_capabilities`) that a v1.0 binary reads before any mutating or\nexternally-publishing operation, failing closed on an unknown version or required\ncapability while keeping reads and diagnostics available. (Readiness Finding 2 —\nverified VALID against `src/rebar/_store/ensures.py`, `src/rebar/reducer/_version.py`,\n`src/rebar/_commands/{compact,fsck,init}.py`, `docs/migrations.md`.)\n\n## Why\n\nrebar's migration mechanism is an idempotent desired-state ensure-registry, not an\nordered ledger: `run_ensures` runs every unit under the write lock, converts\nexceptions to `failed`, and **returns normally** (`src/rebar/_store/ensures.py`\ndocstring \"Never raises\"; init/boot never abort). Event compatibility is\npreserve-and-ignore: unknown event types are skipped in replay\n(`reducer/_replay.py:195-196`) and omitted from the compaction fold but kept on\ndisk (`_commands/compact.py:179-195`), and `fsck` emits an informational WARN that\ndoes not increment `issue_count` or stop operation (`_commands/fsck.py:229-252`,\nwhich itself notes \"a reconcile host on an old binary may push stale state\").\n\nThis forward-compat is correct for *optional additive* data — it prevents an old\ncompactor from deleting new bytes. But there is **no committed store-format-version\nor required-capability record** (confirmed absent; `SCHEMA_VERSION` is a stamp,\nnever compared to fail closed). So an old binary computes state that omits the\nunknown event and can then emit a new event, compact, evaluate close/verify policy,\nor push a stale field to Jira from that incomplete state. `docs/migrations.md`\nexplicitly files the \"A-tier ledger + committed store-format version that fails\nclosed\" under future work. **The reader must ship in v1.0**: an already-installed\nv1.0 binary cannot be taught later to inspect a record whose existence and\nsemantics were not defined in v1.0 — so to ever mark a store as requiring a\npost-v1.0 capability, v1.0 must already know how to detect and refuse unknown\nrequired capabilities.\n\n## What\n\nAdopt git's repository-format-version pattern\n(`core.repositoryformatversion` + `extensions.*`: an implementation that does not\nunderstand the advertised format or a required extension must not operate, because\ncontinuing can produce incorrect results or lose data), and git's staged rollout\n(teach readers first, make writing opt-in, default later):\n\n- **The record.** Add a committed store-level record, minimally\n  `{\"format_version\": 1, \"required_capabilities\": []}`, at a fixed store path (e.g.\n  `.store-compat.json`). It is **committed to the `tickets` branch** (not\n  git-ignored) — it is the shared fact the gate reads. Write it with the store's\n  standard write-to-tempfile-then-atomic-rename pattern so a partial/interrupted\n  write never leaves a truncated file.\n- **Recognised-capability vocabulary.** The new module exports\n  `KNOWN_CAPABILITIES: frozenset[str] = frozenset()` — the set of capability strings\n  **this** binary understands. The gate blocks when any entry in a record's\n  `required_capabilities` is not in `KNOWN_CAPABILITIES`. Future capabilities are\n  added to this set only when the feature that consumes them ships (git\n  `extensions.*` semantics).\n- **The gate error.** The module exports `StoreIncompatibleError(Exception)`, raised\n  by the gate; entry-point callers convert it to the existing `CommandError` /\n  non-zero exit path (as other gate errors do), with a message naming the\n  unsupported version/capability.\n- **Four record states (explicit).** (1) **Absent** → implicit legacy format\n  version 0, compatible / pass-through, NOT blocked. (2) **Present + compatible** →\n  pass. (3) **Present + incompatible** (unknown `format_version` or a\n  `required_capabilities` entry ∉ `KNOWN_CAPABILITIES`) → **fail-closed**. (4)\n  **Present + unreadable/corrupt** (JSON parse error, truncation, permission denied)\n  → **fail-closed** with a diagnostic message naming the parse error and the record\n  path (a corrupt record is NOT treated as absent — that would silently bypass the\n  gate).\n- **Expand phase (writing the record into pre-v1.0 stores).** Every store created by\n  a pre-v1.0 build is state (1). An idempotent ensure unit (School B) writes the\n  record at the current version when absent, at init / fsck-repair / MCP-boot.\n  **Because `run_ensures` is fail-silent** (a `LockTimeout` silently skips the whole\n  sweep; exceptions become `failed` and it returns normally), the covered-write path\n  must not *depend* on the ensure sweep having run: the gate treats absent as\n  pass-through regardless, and the record is written opportunistically. So a missed\n  sweep never blocks writes — it only defers stamping the record to a later covered\n  operation. **absent = legacy/needs-migration, not blocked; present-incompatible or\n  corrupt = blocked.**\n- **Gate at the true structural choke point, NOT by enumerating call-sites.** \"No\n  mutation without the gate\" must not rest on a hand-maintained list a future path can\n  bypass. The single convergence point for **all lock-based store mutations** is\n  **`lock.acquire()` in `src/rebar/_store/lock.py`** — both the `write_lock()` context\n  manager AND the direct callers that bypass it (`txn.py`'s `_acquire_write_lock` for\n  claim/transition, `compact.py:167`/`:415`, `fsck.py:419`) call `acquire()`. Insert\n  the `check_store_compat()` gate **inside `lock.acquire()`**, after `canonical_tracker()`\n  resolves the path and before the fcntl/mkdir legs — so every lock-holding path\n  (context-manager and raw-handle) is covered by one insertion point, with no\n  enumeration.\n- **Two paths do NOT go through `lock.acquire()` and each gets its own explicit gate:**\n  1. **`fsck_recover.py`** performs raw `git cherry-pick`/`rebase --continue`/`merge\n     --abort` via its `_git()` helper with **no locking at all** — so it is genuinely\n     un-gated by the lock choke point. Add an explicit `check_store_compat(tracker_dir)`\n     at the top of `fsck_recover_cli` before any mutation. (Wrapping the mutation block\n     in `write_lock` too would additionally close a real pre-existing concurrency gap,\n     but at minimum the explicit gate is required.)\n  2. **Outbound Jira publish** — the push/reconcile side effect is a **remote API\n     call**, not a lock-held write, so gate immediately **before the outbound Jira\n     call is initiated** at the one push entry point (so stale state is never pushed).\n- **Completeness is CI-enforced.** A coverage test/lint greps the tree for **both**\n  `lock.acquire(` and `write_lock(` (and asserts each routes through the gate) plus\n  asserts `fsck_recover_cli` calls `check_store_compat` — so a new un-gated write path,\n  in any of the acquisition forms, fails CI rather than relying on this prose list.\n- **Read/diagnostic allowance.** Under an incompatible/corrupt record, the read-only\n  commands — `fsck`, `show`, `list`, `search` — stay available and report the\n  unsupported version/capability (structured, machine-checkable output).\n- **Rollback safety (concrete).** State the post-rollback file state explicitly: the\n  committed `.store-compat.json` remains on the `tickets` branch unchanged; a\n  pre-v1.0 binary must treat it as an ignored-unknown file (old ensure units only\n  touch `.gitignore`/`.gitattributes`/`.env-id`/etc., and old compaction/fsck do not\n  parse it). **If** a pre-v1.0 binary would parse-and-error on it, the documented\n  compensating-forward path is: delete `.store-compat.json` to restore the implicit\n  legacy state. Confirm which case holds and document it.\n- **Scope boundary.** Keep the ensure-registry for convergent check-then-act repairs.\n  Do **not** build the ordered ledger here — only the record + reader gate. Clarify\n  the relationship to `SCHEMA_VERSION` in `reducer/_version.py` (it stays the\n  event-schema discriminator; `format_version` is the new store-format gate — state\n  whether they move together or independently).\n\n## Scope\n\n- New module under `src/rebar/_store/` for the compatibility record + gate, exporting\n  `StoreIncompatibleError`, `KNOWN_CAPABILITIES`, and `check_store_compat()`.\n- `src/rebar/_store/lock.py` — insert the gate inside `lock.acquire()` (the single\n  convergence point for `write_lock()` + all direct `lock.acquire()` callers:\n  `txn.py`, `compact.py:167`/`:415`, `fsck.py:419`).\n- `src/rebar/_commands/fsck_recover.py` — explicit `check_store_compat()` before its\n  raw-git mutation (it holds no lock, so the `lock.acquire()` gate does not cover it).\n- The outbound Jira push call-site in the reconciler — explicit gate before the API call.\n- A coverage test/lint grepping `lock.acquire(` + `write_lock(` + `fsck_recover`'s check.\n- `src/rebar/reducer/_version.py` — relate `format_version` to the existing\n  preserve-and-ignore `KNOWN_EVENT_TYPES` machinery and to `SCHEMA_VERSION`\n  (optional-additive events stay preserve-and-ignore; a required capability is the\n  new fail-closed path).\n- `src/rebar/_commands/init.py` — the ensure unit that writes the record when absent.\n- `docs/migrations.md` — document the record, the four states, the fail-closed\n  semantics, the absent-record upgrade path, and the concrete rollback state.\n- Interface tests extending `tests/interfaces/contracts/test_event_schema_forward_compat.py`.\n- Out of scope: the ordered migration ledger; changing any existing event-replay\n  behaviour for currently-known types.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] A committed store compatibility record (`format_version` +\n  `required_capabilities`) is created at init at a fixed path, written atomically\n  (tempfile + rename), and read by a gate function that raises\n  `StoreIncompatibleError`; the module exports `KNOWN_CAPABILITIES: frozenset[str]`.\n- [ ] An **absent** record (pre-v1.0 store) is treated as legacy format version 0 /\n  compatible (pass-through, not blocked), and the ensure unit idempotently writes the\n  record on the next init / fsck-repair / MCP-boot — verified by a test that opens a\n  record-less store with a v1.0 build, confirms it operates, and confirms the record\n  is then present (upgrade-in-place, no manual step); the test also confirms a missed\n  ensure sweep does not block writes.\n- [ ] The gate is inserted inside `lock.acquire()` (`src/rebar/_store/lock.py`, after\n  path resolution, before fcntl/mkdir) so every lock-holding mutation — `write_lock()`\n  context-manager callers AND direct `lock.acquire()` callers (`txn.py`, `compact.py`,\n  `fsck.py`) — is covered by one insertion point; plus an explicit\n  `check_store_compat()` at the top of `fsck_recover_cli` (which does raw-git,\n  no-lock mutation) and immediately before the outbound Jira push call. It raises\n  `StoreIncompatibleError` (→ non-zero exit) before any side effect when the record is\n  **present but incompatible**. Verified by (a) a test in\n  `tests/interfaces/contracts/test_event_schema_forward_compat.py` writing a record\n  with a `required_capabilities` entry ∉ `KNOWN_CAPABILITIES` (e.g. `[\"unknown-v99\"]`)\n  and driving a lock-held mutation (store files byte-unchanged), an `fsck_recover`\n  invocation, and a Jira push (mock adapter records zero calls); and (b) a coverage\n  test/lint that greps the tree for **both** `lock.acquire(` and `write_lock(` and for\n  `fsck_recover_cli`'s `check_store_compat` call, asserting each routes through the\n  gate — so a new un-gated write path in any acquisition form fails CI.\n- [ ] A **corrupt/unreadable** record (truncated JSON / parse error) is treated as\n  fail-closed (NOT as absent) with a diagnostic naming the parse error and path —\n  verified by a test writing a truncated record and asserting a mutating entry point\n  is blocked.\n- [ ] A rollback **test** (hard requirement) simulates a pre-v1.0 binary — the store\n  layer invoked with the gate code path absent — against a store carrying the\n  committed record, and asserts the store is operable and the record file is\n  byte-unchanged (proving upgrade-in-place won't brick a pre-v1.0 clone). The\n  ignored-unknown guarantee and the delete-`.store-compat.json` compensating path are\n  also documented in `docs/migrations.md`.\n- [ ] Under an incompatible/corrupt record, the read-only commands `fsck`, `show`,\n  `list`, and `search` exit with the read-allowed code (0) and their structured output\n  / stderr (WARNING+) contains the unsupported version/capability identifier —\n  verified by a test asserting the exact field via `jq -e` / an anchored regex.\n- [ ] Optional additive (unknown-but-not-*required*) events retain today's\n  preserve-and-ignore behaviour — the existing forward-compat contract tests still\n  pass, and a new test proves a *required* capability fails closed while an *optional*\n  additive event does not.\n- [ ] `docs/migrations.md` documents the record, the four states, the fail-closed\n  gate, the deployment-order rationale (why the reader ships in v1.0), and the\n  concrete rollback state.\n- [ ] `make lint && make typecheck && make test` pass, and the change lands via the\n  Gerrit two-vote gate."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1784070631006107001,"uuid":"1e027746-113a-4d97-a00f-2035303bb8b8"}